# Architecture Map LLM Guide

## Purpose

Use this command to render a descriptive map of configured modules, layers, cross-module dependencies, unknown files, and hotspots.

## When To Run

- Before deciding where a behavior belongs.
- When onboarding into an unfamiliar codebase.
- Before adding a new dependency between modules.

## How To Read The Result

- Modules show the configured ownership grouping.
- Layer summaries show how files are distributed within each module.
- Dependencies show cross-module import direction and count.
- Unknown files may need classification or may be intentionally outside current rules.

## Examples

- If a behavior belongs to one module but the map shows dependencies from several others, look for an existing public seam before adding imports.
- If a module has no layer summary, inspect whether it is intentionally outside the configured layer model.
- If unknown files appear, avoid editing them until local ownership is clear.
- If a hotspot is also dependency-heavy, plan smaller commits and rerun checks often.

## Agent Tips

- Use module and layer names from the map in your implementation notes.
- If a file is unknown, avoid guessing ownership; inspect local rules first.
- Treat hotspots as risk signals for planning, not automatic failures.
- Pair this with boundaries before changing imports.
